biguous whether the question is referring to a team\\\'s Charter (20) or their Roster for a bout (14). I realize that the question is a direct quote from the literal 1st rule in the book, but it only makes real-world sense when read in conjunction with 1.2.',3),(57,'24.231.188.208',1334342057,924,0,'Question #924: I\\\'m reporting question #924 because ... \r\n\r\n\\\"Only\\\" is NOT in 10.3.4, and that word totally changes the meaning of the sentence. That particular rule is *allowing* players to play with doctor\\\'s clearance. The only thing that would *disallow* previously-injured skaters from playing is the Head Ref\\\'s discretion. There\\\'s not an explicit rule against injured skaters playing.',2),(58,'24.231.188.208',1334342685,10,0,'Question #10: I\\\'m reporting question #10 because ... \r\n\r\nGrammar: \\\"Are\\\" should be \\\"is\\\". \\\"Method\\\" is the subject, and it\\\'s singular. It\\\'s wrong in the rulebook too, but two wrongs don\\\'t make a right. :-)',2),(59,'24.231.188.208',1334343399,707,0,'Question #707: I\\\'m reporting question #707 because ... \r\n\r\nI\\\'m nitpicky about this stuff, often asking NSOs to relabel the inside whiteboard to say \\\"Minutes\\\" instead of \\\"Majors\\\", but this question is needlessly confusing to the test-taker. If you want to press the point of whether a 4th-Minor-Minute is *called* a Major or not, then ask that question specifically.',1),(60,'76.184.101.69',1334372159,771,0,'Question #771: I\\\'m reporting question #771 because ... \r\n\r\n7.5.2.6 Coaches and managers are held to the same standard of sportsmanlike behavior as skaters. If a coach or manager is expelled (see Section 7.5.2.1), that team’s Captain will serve a one (1) minute penalty. However, that penalty does not count towards the skater’s penalty cap (see Section 7.5.1.1.1). \r\n\r\nIn the above case, the captain would be serving a major penalty but it does not count toward her fouling out. \r\n\r\nBTW, I really appreciate you putting th